By contrast, if we know only the future occurrence probability of the scenario s, i.e., P(s), and the decision can be given only once at t = 0, we must explore the optimal pathway x(t) considering all future possible scenarios. In this case, control variables x(t) should be identical across the future scenarios as shown in the case (b) of Fig. 2. When we maximize the expected objective function, the optimal pathway x***(t) is obtained by solving2\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
